Data','[av_one_full first]\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\n<p class=\"western\">When the late Nicolaas Johannes Basson first set foot on a farm known as Alexanderfontein in 1969, he saw potential that few others in the Darling area had seen before  becoming one of the first to plant olive trees and vineyards in the area.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">Today, this legacy is carried forward by his son, a next generation Nicolaas Johannes Basson, who not only shares his fathers name, but also his passion for the area, olives, and of course family.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">With the help of the rest of the Basson family and our dedicated employees, Darling Olives has become a must-do experience for those travelling through Darling. Whether bringing your family for an insightful olive tasting around the main table, or as part of a larger group in our tasting hall, we look forward to sharing our olive passion with you.</p>\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_heading tag=\'h3\' padding=\'10\' heading=\'Our Olives\' color=\'\' style=\'\' custom_font=\'\' size=\'\' subheading_active=\'\' subheading_size=\'15\' custom_class=\'\'][/av_heading]\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\n<p class=\"western\">The Darling Olives estate consists of roughly 70 hectares of dry land olives with about 400 trees per hectare. Being situated about 15km from the ocean as the crow flies, our olive trees only get the cool Atlantic breeze and rain, and are never irrigated. The olives are therefore not artificially fattened with water, but the roots of the trees grow deep into the soil for moisture, resulting in healthy and very tasty olives.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">It takes any cultivar between 5 to 7 years to start producing and 10 to 12 years to come into full production. With our dry land olives it can be up to 20 years for a tree to mature.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">The cultivar on our estate is called Mission  by far the most popular cultivar in South Africa. It originates from San Diego, California (U.S.A.) from seeds that the Franciscan missionaries brought to Mexico. It is a strong grower and the trees can grow up to 15m high.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\">While certain cultivars are only cultivated for their oil or to be used as table olives, \"Mission\" is a triple purpose olive.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><b>First Purpose: Green Olives</b>\r\nWhen the olives turn a lighter green/straw yellow, we harvest them for green pickling olives.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><b>Second Purpose: Olive Oil</b>\r\nWhen the olives are half ripe, they tend to look like small speckled dove eggs. At this stage we harvest them for oil. Depending on the cultivar and when it is picked, during the season an olive may contain between 12% &amp;mdash; 30% oil. Mission olives contain about 22% oil. Most oil is contained in the flesh, but the whole fruit goes through the hammer mill as some oil can be found in the pip as well.</p>\r\n<p class=\"western\"><b>Third Purpose: Black Olives</b>\r\nWhen the olives are completely ripe, they turn black. At this stage we harvest them to be cured and sold as black table olives.</p>\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_full]'),(3622,2,'_avia_builder_shortcode_tree','a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:11:\"av_one_full\";s:7:\"content\";a:3:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:12:\"av_textblock\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:1;}i:1;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:10:\"av_heading\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:2;}i:2;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:12:\"av_textblock\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:3;}}s:5:\"index\";i:0;}}'),(3623,2,'layout',''),(3624,2,'sidebar',''),(3625,2,'footer',''),(3626,2,'header_title_bar',''),(3627,2,'header_transparency',''),(3628,2,'_avia_hide_featured_image','0'),(3629,289,'_menu_item_type','post_type'),(3630,289,'_menu_item_menu_item_parent','0'),(3631,289,'_menu_item_object_id','2'),(3632,289,'_menu_item_object','page'),(3633,289,'_menu_item_target',''),(3634,289,'_menu_item_classes','a:1:{i:0;s:0:\"\";}'),(3635,289,'_menu_item_xfn',''),(3636,289,'_menu_item_url',''),(3638,289,'_menu-item-avia-megamenu',''),(3639,289,'_menu-item-avia-division',''),(3640,289,'_menu-item-avia-textarea',''),(3641,289,'_menu-item-avia-style',''),(3642,290,'_wp_page_template','default'),(3643,290,'_wp_page_template','default'),(3644,290,'_edit_lock','1428418822:1'),(3645,290,'_edit_last','1'),(3646,290,'_aviaLayoutBuilder_active','active'),(3647,290,'_aviaLayoutBuilderCleanData','[av_one_full first]\r\n[av_heading heading=\'Join us for a tasting\' tag=\'h4\' style=\'blockquote modern-quote\' size=\'\' subheading_active=\'\' subheading_size=\'15\' padding=\'10\' color=\'\' custom_font=\'\'][/av_heading]\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nAt Darling Olives, we not only produce great-tasting olives, but also offer a great tasting experience so you can discover our range of delicious products right here on the farm.\r\n\r\nOur tasting facilities can accommodate small and large groups, either around our main table or in the tasting hall.\r\n\r\nOur entire range of olive products is available for tasting, except for the bath salts and soap of course. You can look forward to EVOO; Garlic Infused Olive Oil; Olive Chocolate, Jams, Pastes and Rubs; as well as our delicious Black and Calamata Olives.\r\n\r\nBooking is recommended for larger groups, or to avoid disappointment.\r\n\r\n<strong>Tasting Room</strong>\r\nTel: 022 492 3171\r\nEmail: <a href=\"mailto:taste@darlingolives.co.za\">taste@darlingolives.co.za</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Trading Hours</strong>\r\nMondays  Fridays: 9:00  16:00\r\nSaturdays: 9:00  14:00\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n\r\n[av_heading heading=\'How to identify a good olive oil\' tag=\'h4\' style=\'blockquote modern-quote\' size=\'\' subheading_active=\'\' subheading_size=\'15\' padding=\'10\' color=\'\' custom_font=\'\'][/av_heading]\r\n\r\n[av_textblock size=\'\' font_color=\'\' color=\'\']\r\nOlive oil, just like wine, has a colour, nose and palate that can be used to distinguish a good EVOO from a substandard olive oil.\r\n\r\n<strong>Colour</strong>\r\nEVOO can be green or light yellow. When it is golden yellow like whiskey, it is either old or oxidised and must be discarde\r\n\r\nA greener colour just means that the fruit was greener when picked and pressed and will result in oil that will be more bitter, pungent and aromatic. This kind of oil is more popular in the Mediterranean countries where a bitter taste is more popular. The bitterness is the antioxidants that will determine the shelf life of the oil.\r\n\r\nA light yellow colour results from pressing riper olives and will produce a softer and milder oil that is more favoured by the South African palate. South African olive makers often compromise with the uneducated South African palate by washing away the bitterness, but Mediterranean countries prefer the bitter taste in both olives and olive oil.\r\n\r\n<strong>Nose</strong>\r\nThe nose is the aroma of the olive oil. To help your identify the aroma, pour a small amount of oil in a glass and hold it with one hand to heat the oil, while covering the glass with the other. Once you lift your hand, you should smell green, freshly cut lawns  the aroma of a great EVOO.\r\n\r\n<strong>Palate</strong>\r\nThe palate describes what the oil tastes like. You will taste the same grass notes that you smelled and experience a peppery sensation on the sides of the tongue and in the throat. Again, this underwrites a good EVOO. If you only taste pepper, the oil is unbalanced.\r\n\r\nThe fresher the oil, the stronger the pepper sensation will be, but as the oil matures, the pepper will lessen.\r\n[/av_textblock]\r\n[/av_one_full]\r\n\r\n[av_one_half first]\r\n\r\n[av_icon_box position=\'top\' boxed=\'\' icon=\'1\' font=\'entypo-fontello\' title=\'Olive Oil Labelling\' link=\'\' linktarget=\'\' linkelement=\'\' font_color=\'\' custom_title=\'\' custom_content=\'\' color=\'\' custom_bg=\'\' custom_font=\'\' custom_border=\'\']\r\n<p class=\"western\">When buying Olive Oil, one must look for the following on the label</p>\r\n[/av_icon_box]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_half][av_one_half]\r\n\r\n[av_icon_box position=\'top\' boxed=\'\' icon=\'1\' font=\'entypo-fontello\' title=\'History of Olives in South Africa\' link=\'\' linktarget=\'\' linkelement=\'\' font_color=\'\' custom_title=\'\' custom_content=\'\' color=\'\' custom_bg=\'\' custom_font=\'\' custom_border=\'\']\r\n<p class=\"western\">The olive was introduced to the New World by the Spanish colonists in California and Central Chile, and to the Cape by Jan van Riebeeck.</p>\r\n[/av_icon_box]\r\n\r\n[/av_one_half]'),(3648,290,'_avia_builder_shortcode_tree','a:3:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:11:\"av_one_full\";s:7:\"content\";a:4:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:10:\"av_heading\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:1;}i:1;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:12:\"av_textblock\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:2;}i:2;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:10:\"av_heading\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:3;}i:3;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:12:\"av_textblock\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:4;}}s:5:\"index\";i:0;}i:1;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:11:\"av_one_half\";s:7:\"content\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:11:\"av_icon_box\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:6;}}s:5:\"index\";i:5;}i:2;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:11:\"av_one_half\";s:7:\"content\";a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:3:\"tag\";s:11:\"av_icon_box\";s:7:\"content\";a:0:{}s:5:\"index\";i:8;}}s:5:\"index\";i:7;}}'),(3649,290,'layout',''),(3650,290,'sidebar',''),(3651,290,'footer',''),(3652,290,'header_title_bar',''),(3653,290,'header_transparency',''),(3654,290,'_avia_hide_featured_image','0'),(3655,293,'_menu_item_type','post_type'),(3656,293,'_menu_item_menu_item_parent','0'),(3657,293,'_menu_item_object_id','290'),(3658,293,'_menu_item_object','page'),(3659,293,'_menu_item_target',''),(3660,293,'_menu_item_classes','a:1:{i:0;s:0:\"\";}'),(3661,293,'_menu_item_xfn',''),(3662,293,'_menu_item_url',''),(3664,293,'_menu-item-avia-megamenu','